# Core constraints

This project reimplements Wikipedia's Vector 2022 skin as a static Hugo theme, plus a
MediaWiki-style Infobox shortcode. It never depends on a MediaWiki server, PHP, or a
database.

- No code file (JS, TS, CSS/SCSS, HTML/Go-template) exceeds **500–1000 lines**. Split
  before hitting the ceiling, not after.
- Never mix languages in one file — no inline `<style>`/`<script>` in templates.
- One concern per file: one component per CSS file, one behavior per TS module, one page
  region per partial.
- Shortcodes live under `layouts/_shortcodes/` and may use either of two layouts,
  chosen per shortcode:
  - **Flat** (default): `layouts/_shortcodes/<name>.html`. The Hugo-canonical
    single-file layout, callable inline as `{{< name >}}`. Use this for any
    shortcode that is — or might become — a paired shortcode reading `.Inner`,
    and for any shortcode that fits in a single file.
  - **Folder**: `layouts/_shortcodes/<name>/index.html` (with optional supporting
    files like `body.html`, `head.html`, or nested partials). Use this only when
    the shortcode genuinely needs multiple distinct concerns living in separate
    files of the same folder. Note the upstream constraint: in Hugo v0.163.3 a
    folder layout registers the shortcode as `{{< <name>/index >}}` (not
    `{{< <name >}}`), and the AST scanner crashes the build for paired shortcodes
    that reference `.Inner` in this layout — so flat remains the default.
- The built `public/` output must run with zero JS runtime dependencies beyond the
  browser — `node_modules/` is dev-tooling only.
- If a task would require violating any of the above, stop and flag it rather than
  silently exceeding the limit.

Full rationale: `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md` in this repo.
